{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_basso_ver01/data/sn85058246/00206536299/1914012401/0084.xml":{"full_text":"B SATURDAY JANUARY 24 1914 THE LOQAN REPUBLICAN PAGE THREE\nI SPEECH OF HON. WILLIAM E.\nI HUMPHREY OF WASHINGTON\nI In the House of Representatives, on Tues., Jan. 13, '14.\nH Tho House had under consideration\ntho resolution (H. Res. 340) refer\nI ring certain portions of the annual\nI message- of tho President of tho Unl\nI ted States to committees.\nI Mr. Humphrey of Washington\nI Mr. Speaker, a few days ago I pro-\nsentcd to the House a list of 227 lum\nI tier and Bhlngle mills in my Btato that\nI were closed on the first day of last\nI December Just to demonstrate the\nI great blessing that had fallen upon\nthe country since It had been so dl-\nvlnoiy favored by free trade and De\nI rnocracy. Some of my Democratic\nB friends seemed to be somewhat per-\nturbe'd and resentful because I did\nI this. They did not and they havo\nI rot and they can not dispute tho\nI facts, but they suld that we on this\nside of tho Housn were preaching cal-\numlty.\nH Tho list of closed mills that I read\nI nt that tlmo tell a story of panic and\ndepression, of Idleness and poverty, so\nInsignificant in comparison with tho\nI list that I now hold In my hand and\nI which I propose to lay before the\nH House as to seem of llttlo Import.\nI Supposo that it is ttdmltted that tho\nI presentation of these facts and figures\nas to tho business conditions of tho\nH5 country is preaching calamity; why\nU -should a Democrat complain? For 10\nI years of unexampled proaporltyi they\n5j unceasingly howled calamity; now\njj tbht wo have calamity, they aro Indlg-\nnant because tho facts are told. To\nJ preach calamity when there Is nono\nI Is Democratic; to preach it when it\nI exists is Republican.\nI As I started to say, our Democratic\nI friends are fearfully agitated because\nI wc tell the facts But truth and\nI Democracy to eath are seldom happy\nI companions. If preaichlng calamity Is\nsin, then even our honored Speaker\n1? hardly in a position to cast the first\netone, or even the last ojhe. Compar\nI ed with the doleful predictions, tear-\nI ful tales, and mournful exhortations\nthat have come from the sad apid elo\nquent lips of the Speaker In days gone\nby, the lamentations of Holy Writ are\nnt: paeans of praise. In those day?\nthere was prosperity everywhere but\nthe smoke of Industry painting th3\nsk tho 3peo;ker could not see and\nthe hum of countless wheels ho could\nziot hear. But now amid tho gloom\nend silence of closing mills and dying\nflres he Is Impresofid with prosperity.\nThe Speaker reminds me of an old\nI gentleman I knew in my early days\nvben I ilved In Indiana. Ho was\nlike tho Speaker something of a phi\nlosopher and somowha,t emphatic In\nhis lajnguage. Ho was greatly troubled\nwith tho toothache One day I met\nhira and said to him, Uncle Roaso,\nhow is your toothache? Ho said, Woll\nyou know I havo had the toothache so\nlong that I never notice It afry more\nunless the damn thing stops.\nWhen I talked tho othor day I ex\nhibited tho list ot closed mills in tho\nstate of Waahln&ton. That list has\nbeen considerably Increased slnco\nthat tlmo. But I did not Intend to to\nfer to that fact. There wero, some In\nsinuations beforo thart tho condition\ncomplalnod of were merely local. This\ntlmo I do not iroposo to go to tho\nPacific coast; I expect to read a story\nof disaster and business depression\nhero in tho East.\nHero Is a list giving tho name and\nlocation of 123 stool mills that woro\nall running a year ago, representing\nnn annual output of 12,800,000 tons\nor 38 per cent of tho entlro produc\ntion of tho entire nation.\nNow, lot somo Democrat nrlso nnd\nfay whothor that Is preaching calam\nity without facts to baso It upon. T\nwill read a list of tho mills and tho\nlo'calltlcs.\nMr. Itccd I supposo tho gentleman\nknows that somo of those factories\nwhich ho presumably has In tho list\nhavo slnco resumed operations, ac\ncording to tho accounts In tho nows\npapors from which I presumo ho com\npiled his statistics.\nMr. Humphroy of Washington Tho\ngentloman knows no such thing. Hero\nIs wlwt tho gentleman doos know,\nI thought somo one on that side would\nnsk such a question, so I sent a wire\nto Clovoltind to f.nd out about tho\nfacts and I havo hero In my hand tho\nTeply, which Is addressed to mo and\nwhich I rocolved about twenty min\nutes ago:\nCleveland, Ohio, Jan. 13, 1914.\nCongressman W. E. Humphrey,\nWashington, D. C,\nOfficials of Steel Corporation and\nlargo Independent mills at Pittsburgh\nadvise they aro not putting hny addi\ntional men to work at this tlmo. In\ndications now point to continued clos\ning down of steel mills and blast fur\nnaces. Reductions of working forces\nof men engaged In all metal working\ntiades, and wage reductions havo al\nready begun. This description of ac\ntually prevailing industrial conditions\napplies to all iron, steel, and other\nmetal working districts throughout\ntbls country. Daily Iron Trade.\nI wired and asked the Dally Iron\nTrado whother the statement which\nappeared In yesterday's paper that\n50,000 men were to be put to work\nin Pittsburgh was true. What I have\nJust read Is the reply. There is an\nother thing that 1 would like to havo\neome gentleman on that sldo answer.\nHow could they put 50,000 men to\nwork again if they hovo never been\nidle? You havo beon constantly de\nnying that there was any truth in such\na statement; but supposo they havo\nput 60,000 men to work that num\nber would only represcent 2 per cent\nof the men that were ldlo on tho first\nday of January of this year and since\nI have compiled this list there are\nothor mills that havo been colsed.\nI want to call attention to this list\nof 123 furnaces by states. In Pennsyl\nvania 53 furnaces have been closed,\nrepresenting an output of ,804,000\ntons. In Alabama there was four fur\nnaces closed, representing an output\n1 of 276,000 tons. It is worthy of notice\nthat three ot these furnaces are situ\n'ated In the city of Birmingham, the\nhome of the distinguished gentlomah\nwhoso name the tariff bill bears. His\nexplanation of this action ot tho mills\nIn his state would be at least interest\ning. In Illinois there are 10, repre\nsenting an output of 795,000 tons.\nIn New York, 10, representing an\noutput of 1,139,000 totas. In Ohio,\nwhich comes second In production to\nPennsylvania, there were 25', repre\nsenting 3,475,000 tons. In Tennessee\nthere tire 8, representing an output\nof 286,000 tons. In Virginia! there\n'ore 3, representing 100,000 tons. In\nWisconsin, there are 2, representing\n130,000 tons. In Colorado 2, represent\nIng 240,000 tons\nIf anyono denies that any furnace\nIn the list is not closed, I will bo\nglad to correct It. I am taking my\nstatement from a trado paper that as\nsures mo they ato correct, Indiana\nI has 3, representing 290,000 tons. Mary\nland 2, representing 96,000 tons. West\nVirginia 2, representing 216,000 tons.\nA total representing an annual output\nof 12,598,000 tons, or 38 per cent of\ntho entlro output of tho lrofn tind\nstool trade In this country and every\nl one of thoso mills were running when\nthe Democratic party went Into power\nI Just want to summarize- now, be\ncause the insinuation has been mado\nen that sldo of tho House was mado\nthe other day by tho Speaker that\nwhen we mado theso statements wo\n1 were doing It without facts upon\nwhich to baso them. I want to dial\nI lengo anybody upon that sldo of tho\nHouse, hero or horcafter, to dispute\ntho correctness ot theso figures. You\nnsk why Is it that wo mako thoso\nI statements. In tho first placo tho\nDemocratic party, backed by tho\nPresident, has repeatedly assured us\nthat If any of theso mills closed that\nnn Investigation would bo mado to as\ncertain why thoy closed Now, I aim\ngoing to put this list In tho Record,\nwhere tho Secretary of Commorco enn\nseo tho namo and tho exact locution\nof each closed mill, where Secretary\nof Lnbor can also havo this Informa\ntion In detail. These two Cnhlnot of\nficials havo repeatedly boasted thoy\nwould Investigate any Industry that\nclosed nnd let tho country know tho\nfacts. I especially call tho attention\nof Secretary Wilson to tho conditions\nIn Pennsylvania.\nIn his own stato there aro 500,000\nmen ldlo that wero at work a fow\nweeks ago. Will ho lnvestlgato nnd\ntoll tho nation why? I askod Sec\nrotary Redfiold some days ago to ln\nvestlgato tho closing of shlnglo and\nlumbor mills In Washington, hut all\nthat li03 come of It Is a promise ot\nduo consideration. I ask theso distin\nguished gontlomon to either do some\nthing or admit that thoy wero simply\nplaying tho very cheap gamo of poli\ntical bluff. I want theso two distin\nguished statesmen that havo talked so\nmuch to lnvestlgato a llttlo.\nI want to know whether theso milts\naro closed; and if thoy are, I want to\nknow whether the men who closed\nthem aro to bo helped or hanged, be\ncauso If they are going to hang Hll\ntho man who havo been responsible\nfor the recent closing of industries In\nthis nation upon a scaffold 50 cublcs\nhigh, as the President said while It\nmay be hard on the guilty wretches,\nIt is certainly going to help the lum\nber business In my country. Now,\nanother thing: The distinguished lead\ner of this House (Mr. Underwood)\nstood upon that side and declared that\nthe Secretary of Labor had the power\nthat ho had tho means, and that it\nany ot theso mills closed, It any legi\ntimate Industry was Injured that an\nInvestigation would bo had and If an\nInjustice had been dono ajny legitimate\nIndustry that that side of tho House\nwould correct tho law. I want to\nknow whother you aro gong to mako\ngood that promise or not. Were you\nsimply making It for political pur\nposes or did you mean It? Havo you\ntho list to investigate.\nLook at tho list. Rend It.\nThis Is tho story in the Iron and\nsteel business:\nEighty-seven days of tho now frco\ndom and frco trado.\nMoro than ono third of all steel\nmills In the United States closed.\nMoro than 1,000,000 men ldlo.\nMoro than $2,000,000 a day In wages\ngono.\nMore than $125,000,000 Invested In\nclosed mills.\nAn annual pay roll of moro than\n1746,000,000 wiped out.\nYet It Is proposed to make still fur\nther assaults upon American indus\ntries, and any man that dare cry out\nagainst it la to be written down as a\ncriminal. Amd still the Democratic,\nparty and my distinguished friend who\nJust took hig seat (Mr. Read) wants\nyou to believe that this nation can\nprosper under free trade.\nMr. Reed I do not think there was\nanythlnu in my statement that had\nanything whatever to do with pros\nperity under free trade. I am per\nfectly willing that the gqntleman shall\ncriticise my speech, but I want him\ntc do It by confining himself absolute\nly to tho truth and not by drawing\nconclusions that aro not warranted by\nmy speech.\nMr. Humphrey of Washington It\ntho gentleman had draw'n that rule\non himself, no reply from mo would\nhavo \"beon necessary. There would\nnot havo been any speech from him.\nMr. Fowler I would bo glad If tho\ngentloman will give tho nnlmes of tho\nIllinois steel plants that havo closed\ndown.\nMr. Humphrey ot Washington\nWith-pleasure. Ono Is tno Fedoral\nFurnace Co., of Chicago, with an an\nnual output of 85,000 tons. Another is\ntho Iroquois Iron Co., of Chicago, with\non annual ouput of 120,00 tons. Still\nanother Is tho Illinois Steel Co., of\nChicago with an annual output of 590-\n000 tons.\nThen dropping down to Indiana,\nnear Chicago, I find that tho Indiana\nSteel Co., Indiana Harbor, with an\naiVnunrt output ot 120,000 tons, hns\nclosed down; also tho Indiana Steel\nCo., at Gary, a suburb ot Chicago,\nwith un annual' output of 170,000 tons.\nMr. Fowler Tho gentleman does\nnot mean to say that tho Gary steel\nplaint has closed down, does ho?\nMr. Humphrey of Washington I re\nsay that thoso I have mentioned havo\nclosed down.\nMr. Fowler Is It not a fact that\ntho Illinois Steel Plant and tho Illinois\nSteel Corporation aro both in opera\ntion today?\nMr. Humphrey of Washington\nWell, tho gentleman hals my statement.\n1 havo put It In the Record, where tho\ngentleman enn find It.\nMr. Fowler I nm asking tho gentlo\nman Is not that ii fact?\nMr. Humphrey of WnshlngtonI re\nply to tho gentleman that theso com\npanics I havo mentioned havo closed.\nMr. Fowlor And thoy are nothing\nelso than adjuncts or subordinates,\nwhich aro usually closed overy season\nmore or loss.\nMr. Humphrey of Washington Us\nually less. Nono of them wero closed\na year ngorf\nMr. Langloy Thoy aro usually clos\ned down under a Democratic adminis\ntration.\nMr. Humphrey of Washington Tho\ncondition of tho Iron and steel trado in\ntho United States on tho first day of\nJanuary, 1911, is reviewed In an nr\ntlclo on tho first page of tho Dally\nIron Trado of Friday, January 9, 1914.\nThis is not a political paper; It docs\nnot attempt to fix responsibility or\ngive tho causo for present conditions;\nit simply, In a cold business manner,\nstates tho facts. Tho article opens\nwith this sontonco:\nTho astounding depth to which tho\nbusiness depression of the Unitod\nSlates and especially tho Iron and\nsteel business, has sunk In tho past\nsix months makes ono of tho stupen\ndous stories of tho past fifty years.\nTho article then proceeds to sot\nout In detail tho present conditions,\not this great Industry which Is uni\nversally regarded as tho host busi\nness barometer In tho United States.\nTho filets, when known, will stagger\ntho American people\nOn tho 4th day of March last, when\ntho Democratic party came Into pow\ner, tho steel and Iron business of tho\ncountry was almost at thu very height\nof Its prosperity. On that day, as I\nhavo alreaidy pointed out, there wero\n306 blast furnaces running. On the\nfirst day of January, 1914, there were\n123 of Uieso furnaces closod. Thirty\neight per cent of all tho fires In thq\nblast furnaces In tho United Statos\naro now out, with no prospect of again\nbeing relighted.\nMr. Cox I want to nsk tho gentlo;,\nman it thoso closures are brought\nabout by tho Importation of iron and\nsteel?\nMr. Humphrey of Washington\nThey have been brought about by\ntho tariff bill that tho Democratic\nparty placed on tho statute books.\nMr. Cox I would ltko to have tho\ngentleman answer my question. I do\nnot think lib answered It yet to suit\nme.\nMr. Humphrey of Washington I\ndo not expect to be ablo to answer\nany question In a way to suit tho\ngentleman. I havo no Idea that I\ncould possibly do It.\nMr. Cox I will put tho question,\nhgaln. Have these mills been closed\ndown as tho result of tho importation\not iron and steel slnco Democratic\ntnrlff bill went Into effect?\nMr. Humphrey of Washington Oho\nc( the reasons why thoy havo closod\ndown Is hecauso uqdor tho present\ntariff law business throughout tho Uni\nted States generally has been nbso\nluly, paralyzed and there Is no demand\nfor steel. That is tho reajson.\nMr. Cox Then it has not been due\nto tho importation of steel under tho\nDemocratic tariff law as I understand?\nMr. Humphrey of Washington As\nfar as that is concerned tho people\nof tho United States aro not buying\neither at homo or abroad at this tlmo.\nMr. Cox I want the gentleman to\nanswer this question, If ho Is prepar\ned to do It: What amount of stool nnd\nIron has been imported into tills coun-i\ntry slnco tills bill wont into effect, as\ncompared with what It was last year,\nMr. Humphrey of Washington I\ndo not know. I know that tho homo\nproduction has decreased over ono\nthird.\nMr. Hardy Will tho gentleman al\nso answer as to whothor or not lum\nbor mills havo been closed irt all by\nImportations ot lumber Into this coun\ntry, and whether there hns boon nny\nIncrenso In Importations of lumber?\nMr. Humphrey of Washington' 1\ndo not know whother there has been\nJ.ny Increaso In tho Importation ol\nlumber or not. I know that tho lum\nber mills of my country nro closed.\nI know that tho largest mill In the\nstato of Washington closed about 3\nweeks ago for tho first tlmo In 55\nyears. For tho last 2 yoajrs nnd prob\nnbly longer It hns run day and night.\nIt even survived tho hwful days ol\n'93-97. Tho president ot this com\npany Is hero, and ho may bo Inside ot\nthis hall now for aught I know and\nfrom him I recolved this Information,\nMr. Hardy My understanding ol\ntho argument of Ropubllcnns has al\nways been that tho Democratic law\nwould pormlt Importations In compo;\ntltlon with our products, and thoreby\ndoprlvo our Industries of tholr cm\nployment. Now, I want to know 11\nthe tnrlff has brought In any Increased\nnimount of lumbor or an Increased\namount of machinery or of iron prod\nucts, and has had any such result.\nMr. Humphrey of Washington Tho\ngentleman attributes to tho Republi\ncan party an argument that tho Re\npublican pnrty docs not mako\nTho argument of tho Republican\nparty la that under frco trado you\nstop production. You stop tho do-,\nmnnd. You throw men out of employ\nment nnd stop tho payment of wages.\nYou pnrnlyzo tho entlro Industrial\nsystem of tho country, nnd under n\nDemocratic administration you can\nnelthor buy nt homo nor abroad.\nCheap goods nro of no valuo to tho\nldlo without money.\nMr Copley' This may bo nn an\nswer to tho questions that hnvo boon\nasked from tho other sldo. Probably\ntho gentloman knows that within tho\nlast two woeks ono enrgo of corn that\nstarted from Argentina to this coun\ntry reduced tho price of tho farmers\ncorn In tho United Slates moro thhn\n10 cents a bushel on the exrhnngo In\nChicago It does not need tho Impor\ntation of ono slnglo bushel at the\npresent tlmo, but tho threat of com\ning Importation has decreased tho\nprice of corn.\nMr. Fess That Is what tho Demo\ncratic party promised a reduction of\ntho prices of farm products.\nMr. Humphrey of Washington I\nhave a clipping on my desk which\nstates that 5,000,000 bushels ot corn\nhavo beon contracted for from Ar\ngentina). Mr. Fess I want to ask tho gentle\nman If tho Democrats did not say\nthoy would reduce tho prico ot tho\nproducts of tho farm 7\nMr. Humphrey of Washington\nThoy did when thoy wore In tho cities\nbut when thoy woro In tho country\nthey said thoy would Increase tho\nprices of farm products.\nxH must not bo forgotten that con\nnected with tho Iron, steel nnd met\nals trado aro 28,800 separnto and dis\ntinct establishments. Theso allied\nestablishments employ moro than\n2,000,000 men. Thoro aro all direct\nly affected.\nIt must not bo forgotten that thoro\nate 958,000 mines that aro directly\nnffoctcd by this depression In tho stool\nindustry. The output of bituminous'\ncoal has decreased between 40 and\n&G per cent.\nThoro nlro 270,000 miners In tho\nUnited States now out of work and\nthis does not include nbout 50,000 In\ntho iron mines of tho Lako Superior\nregion who aro annually out ot em\nployment at this season of 'the year.\nThe wage earners aro losing G3,:\n000,000 per month.\nTwo billion dollars a day thatt tho\nAmerican workmen wero receiving a,\ntew months ago has been taken from\nthem and paid to tho foreigner or not\npaid at all.\nIs it any wonder, with this vast\nsum of moro than 12,000,000 por\nday taken from labor within tho last\nfow months, that there Is gonoral\nbusiness paralysis?\nAt least 90 per cent of this great\nsum Is taken out of tho channels of H\ntrado. Business feels It ovorywhere; f H\nit shows In the condition of overy H\ntrade; it affects overy community. H\nTho tremendous and startling slid- H\nden Increnso In tho number of ldlo H\nrailway cars in tho country within H\ntho last fow months tells 1 na grahlep jM\nthe Inst fow months tolls in a graphics 'H\nstory tho business conditions, of tho H\nOn tho first day of November, 1913 H\nthere was In tho country a shortage H\nof railway cars totaling 1,842. FIN H\nteen dny'a la,ter, November tho 15th t\nthere wero 22,205 ldlo cars. H\nFifteen days later Decombcrl H\nthere wero 51,451 ldlo cars! H\nJanuary 1, 1914, thoro woro 188,850 M\nldlo cars. M\nOr, In sixty days, thoro was a do- H\ncroaso in tho domand for cars to con- M\nduct tho business of tho country of tho M\nastounding number of 190,692. M\nThe tariff law fell upon tho lumber H\nand shlnglo Industries upon tho Pa- M\nctflc coast like an earthquake In the M\nnight, but its effect soems to have M\nbeen equally disastrous and equally M\nsudden upon the great Iron and stool M\nIndustry and the ratlroajds of tho na M\nqn tho first day of January, 1913., M\nonly a year ago, the United States M\nSteel Co., had orders amounting to M\n7,852,000 tons. M\nOn tho first day ot January, 1914, M\nit had orders amounting to 4,250,000 H\nTheso decreases tell in graphic story M\ntho general condition of tho steel in- H\ndustry today. Tho most radical pro-\ntcctlonlst would not havo dared to H\nprophesy such wldo and universal dls- H\naster by less than threo months of\nfrco trado.\nHero nro somo specific Instances of H\ntho number of men that havo been H\ndischarged and are now ldlo: H\nPennsylvania Steel Co., 4,000. M\nLackawanna Steel Co., 4,000. H\nBethlehem Steel Co., 4,000. M\nIllinois and Indiana Stoel Cos., 7000. H\nCarneglo Steel Co., 10,000. M\nJones McLaughlin, 6,000. M\nBaldwin Locomotlvo Works, 4,000., M\nUnited States Steel Co., over 40,- M\nAlan Wood Iron Stool Co., 1000. M\nAmerican Locomotlvo Works, at H\nRichmond, Va., 3,000. M\nAmerican Locomotlvo Works, other M\nplaces, 5000. H\nIn tho automobile Industry the fol- H\nlowing men havo been discharged: H\nCleveland, Ohio, over 3,000. H\nIn the Detroit district and adjacent ,H\nterritory, 35,000. M\nIndianapolis and other centers In H\ntho mlddlo west 12,000. H\nI quote again from the artlclo In\nthe Daily Iron Trado: (H\nAided by conservative calculation H\nmado at leading industrial and trade H\ncenters by ataff representatives ot H\ntho Dally Iron Trade, tho past ten H\ndays show that over 1,000,000 work M\n(Continued from pago four) H\nMid-Winter I\nEXCURSION I\nTO H\nCALIFORNIA 1\nVIA H\nOregon Short Line I\nand H\nSalt Lake Route I\nJANUAR Y 31, FROM UTAH POINTS H\nLMlTMARCh 16, 1914. H\nRound Trip From Logan H\nto Los Angeles through H\nSalt Lake- City H\n$38.15 I\nTlckots on sale on samo date to\nLos Angeles via Portland and O. H\nW. R. N. and via Ogden and H\ntho Southern Pacific at proportion- H\nntoly low rates.\nThree Special Trains H\nwill be operated out of Salt Lake City via the Salt fH\nLake Route, leaving Salt Lake Union Depot 11:00 E\na. m., January 31st, arriving Los Angeles 'the follow- jH\ning aftcrnoon--ony one night enroute. These trains jH\nwill be personally conducted and will consist of the 'M\nmost up-to-date standard and tourist sleepers, buffet WW\nobservation cars and diners. M\nFor further particulars consult any Oregon Short iB\nLine Agent write jH\nD. E. BURLEY, Gen. Passenger Agt., fl\nI' Salt Lake City, Utah ;\"M","height":"25168","width":"17728"}}
